      <div class="bento-card">
        <div class="bento-num">✗</div>
        <h3 class="bento-title">Skip Wordtune if</h3>
        <h4 class="bento-sub">You need <span class="accent">SEO content written and published</span> automatically.</h4>
        <p class="bento-desc">Business owners targeting Google rankings, content teams running blogs at scale, local businesses needing GBP management. Wordtune polishes sentences — it doesn't build a content strategy.</p>
        <div class="bento-cta">See why theStacc fits better <span class="arrow">↓</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHAT IS WORDTUNE -->
  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">What is Wordtune</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">An <span class="accent">AI-powered writing assistant</span> for sentence-level clarity and tone.</h2>
      <p>Wordtune is an AI-powered writing assistant developed by AI21 Labs that rephrases individual sentences, adjusts tone, and enhances clarity in real-time. Operating as a browser extension for Chrome and Edge, a web editor, a Microsoft Word add-in, and a Google Docs integration, it generates alternative phrasings when users highlight text. The tool serves 10 million users who collectively generated over 782 million rewrite suggestions. It uses proprietary Jurassic language models optimized for semantic understanding rather than simple synonym replacement.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col after" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <p style="color: var(--text-2); margin: 0 0 16px;">What makes Wordtune different from basic paraphrasers is context-awareness. Instead of swapping words for synonyms, it reads the sentence meaning and generates alternatives that preserve intent while varying style. That's genuinely useful for non-native English speakers and professionals who know what they want to say but not quite how to say it.</p>
        <p style="color: var(--text-2); margin: 0 0 16px;">What Wordtune can't do: it can't rewrite paragraphs or maintain narrative flow across sections, it has zero SEO capability, it can't create original content from scratch, and it can't publish anything anywhere. AI21 Labs halted active development in April 2025 — the tool is operational but no new features are coming.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PROS / CONS -->
  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">The honest pros & cons</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">What Wordtune gets right — <span class="accent">and where it lets you down.</span></h2>
      <p>We ran Wordtune across professional emails, academic summaries, content rewrites, and tone adjustments. Here's what we found.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col after">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">Pros</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">Where Wordtune shines</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">Five strengths that hold up under real use.</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Context-aware sentence rewriting that beats synonym swappers</h4>
              <p>Wordtune's Jurassic models read sentence meaning and generate alternatives that preserve intent. The rewrites are noticeably better than tools that just swap synonyms — they read as written by a human, not a thesaurus.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Granular tone control per sentence</h4>
              <p>Casual, Formal, Shorten, and Expand modes apply to individual sentences. You can make one sentence more formal while keeping the next conversational — more control than tools that apply tone to entire documents.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Spices feature with cited facts and analogies</h4>
              <p>Spices generates examples, analogies, and statistical facts with hyperlinked sources you can verify. Genuinely useful when you need to add evidence or an illustration mid-draft without researching from scratch.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">04</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Wordtune Read for long document summarization</h4>
              <p>Condenses documents up to 500 pages into scannable summaries with links back to the source material. Students and researchers save real time here — it's one of the more polished summarization tools in the category.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">05</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Cross-platform extension that works where you already write</h4>
              <p>Gmail, LinkedIn, Slack, Google Docs, Microsoft Word, Outlook — the extension drops Wordtune into your existing workflow. Smart Paste reformats pasted content for the destination platform automatically.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="ba-col before">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">Cons</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">Where Wordtune falls short</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">Five honest weaknesses we ran into.</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Zero SEO capability — not even keyword suggestions</h4>
              <p>No keyword research, no content optimization, no competitor analysis, no publishing automation. If you're trying to rank on Google, Wordtune has nothing for you. It improves writing quality, not search visibility.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Sentence-level only — can't touch paragraphs</h4>
              <p>Highlight a sentence: great results. Highlight a paragraph: the coherence breaks down. It can't restructure article sections or maintain narrative flow across passages. A real limitation for content writers.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Development halted since April 2025</h4>
              <p>AI21 Labs stopped active Wordtune feature development. The tool works, but no improvements are coming. For a subscription product in a fast-moving AI landscape, that's a significant risk — competing tools improve monthly.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">04</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Restrictive free plan limits real evaluation</h4>
              <p>10 rewrites per day and 3 monthly summaries. Most users hit the cap on day one and can't evaluate the tool properly before being pushed to paid. A 3-day free trial helps but doesn't fully solve it.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">05</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Grammar checking underperforms Grammarly</h4>
              <p>In direct comparison testing, Grammarly catches more grammar errors with fewer false positives. If grammar accuracy is the primary need, Wordtune is the wrong tool — Grammarly is $12/month and better at it.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- STATS ROW -->
  <section>
    <div class="stats-row">
      <div class="stat-cell"><div class="stat-num">10M<span class="accent">+</span></div><div class="stat-label">Users served</div></div>
      <div class="stat-cell"><div class="stat-num">$6.99<span class="accent">+</span></div><div class="stat-label">Starting monthly (annual)</div></div>
      <div class="stat-cell"><div class="stat-num">3.8<span class="accent">/5</span></div><div class="stat-label">Average rating · 4,200+ reviews</div></div>
